# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerotolerant-anaerobe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/aerotolerant-anaerobe] There are three categories of anaerobes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/aerotolerant-anaerobe] Where obligate aerobes require oxygen to grow, obligate anaerobes are damaged by oxygen, aerotolerant organisms cannot use oxygen but tolerate its presence, and facultative anaerobes use oxygen if it is present but can grow without it.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/aerotolerant-anaerobe] Most aerotolerant anaerobes have superoxide dismutase and (non-catalase) peroxidase but do not have catalase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/aerotolerant-anaerobe] More specifically, they may use a NADH oxidase/NADH peroxidase (NOX/NPR) system or a glutathione peroxidase system.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/aerotolerant-anaerobe] An example of an aerotolerant anaerobe is *Cutibacterium acnes*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] An **anaerobic organism** or **anaerobe** is any organism that does not require molecular oxygen for its growth.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] It may react negatively or even die in the presence of free oxygen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Anaerobic organisms do not use oxygen as a terminal electron acceptor in their respiration process to produce energy, but a less powerful oxidizing agent, such as nitrate, ferric ion, Mn(IV), sulfate or bicarbonate anions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] In contrast, an aerobic organism (aerobe) is an organism that requires a sufficiently oxygenated environment to respire, produce its energy, and thrive.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] However, a minuscule multicellular organism, with an exceptionally rare metabolism and surviving in a hypersaline brine pool in the darkness of the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea, has been recently discovered.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Meanwhile, it remains a scientific curiosity, as the much higher energy requirements of most multicellular organisms cannot be met by anaerobic respiration.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The deep seafloor and its underlying unconsolidated sediments ranks among the largest potential habitats for anaerobic microorganisms on Earth.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Moreover, chemoautotroph microbes also thrive around hydrothermal vents, discharging hot water on the ocean seabed near mid-ocean ridges, where anaerobic conditions prevail.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] These microbes produce energy in the absence of sunlight or oxygen through a process called anaerobic respiration, whereby inorganic compounds and ions such as protons (H+), elemental sulfur and its derivatives (SO2−4, S2O2−3), or ferric ions, are reduced to drive oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] In his 14 June 1680 letter to the Royal Society, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek described an experiment he carried out by filling two identical glass tubes about halfway with crushed pepper powder, to which some clean rain water was added.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Van Leeuwenhoek sealed one of the glass tubes with a flame and left the other open.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] In 1913, Martinus Beijerinck repeated Van Leeuwenhoek's experiment and identified *Clostridium butyricum* as a prominent anaerobic bacterium in the sealed pepper infusion tube liquid.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Some obligate anaerobes use fermentation, while others use anaerobic respiration.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Aerotolerant organisms are strictly fermentative.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] In the presence of oxygen, facultative anaerobes use aerobic respiration.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] In the absence of oxygen, some facultative anaerobes use fermentation, while others may use anaerobic respiration.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] There are many anaerobic fermentative reactions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The energy released in this reaction (without ADP and phosphate) is approximately 150 kJ per mol, which is conserved in generating two ATP from ADP per glucose.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] This is only 5% of the energy per sugar molecule that the typical aerobic reaction generates.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The energy released is about 180 kJ/mol, which is conserved when 2 ATP are generated from 2 ADP per glucose.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Anaerobic bacteria and archaea use these and many other fermentative pathways, e.g., propionic acid fermentation, butyric acid fermentation, solvent fermentation, mixed acid fermentation, butanediol fermentation, Stickland fermentation, acetogenesis, or methanogenesis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Creatine, an organic compound found in animals, provides a way for ATP to be utilized in the muscle.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The phosphorylation of creatine allows for the storage of readily available phosphate that can be supplied to the muscles.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The reaction is reversible as well, allowing cellular ATP levels to be maintained during anoxic conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] This process in animals is seen to be coupled with metabolic suppression to allow certain fish, such as goldfish, to survive environmental anoxic conditions for a short period.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Since normal microbial culturing is done in atmospheric air, which contains molecular oxygen, culturing anaerobes requires special techniques.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The Gas-pak System is an isolated container that achieves an anaerobic environment by the reaction of water with sodium borohydride and sodium bicarbonate tablets, which produce hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Hydrogen then reacts with oxygen gas on a palladium catalyst to produce more water, thereby removing oxygen gas.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The issue with the Gas-Pak method is that an adverse reaction can occur, leading to bacterial death; therefore, a thioglycolate medium should be used.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The thioglycolate supplies a medium mimicking that of a dicot plant, thus providing not only an anaerobic environment but all the nutrients needed for the bacteria to multiply.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] On May the 6 2018, a French team evidenced a link between redox and gut anaerobes based on clinical studies of severe acute malnutrition.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] These findings led to the development of an aerobic culture of "anaerobes" by the addition of antioxidants in the culture medium.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Very few multicellular life forms are anaerobic, since only aerobic respiration can provide enough energy for a complex metabolism.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Exceptions include three species of *Loricifera* (< 1 mm in size) and the 10-cell *Henneguya zschokkei*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] In 2010, three species of anaerobic *Loricifera* were discovered in the hypersaline anoxic L'Atalante basin at the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] They lack mitochondria, which contain the oxidative phosphorylation pathway, which in all other animals combines oxygen with glucose to produce metabolic energy; thus, they consume no oxygen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Instead, these *loricifera* derive their energy from hydrogen, using hydrogenosomes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Anaerobic respiration and its end products can facilitate symbiosis between anaerobes and aerobes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] This occurs across taxa, often in compensation for nutritional needs.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Anaerobiosis and symbiosis are found in interactions between ciliates and prokaryotes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Anaerobic ciliates interact with prokaryotes in an endosymbiotic relationship.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] These relationships are mediated in which the ciliate leaves end products that its prokaryotic symbiont utilizes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The ciliate achieves this through fermentative metabolism.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The rumen of various animals houses this ciliate alongside many other anaerobic bacteria, protozoans, and fungi.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] In specific, methanogenic archaea found in the rumen acts as a symbiont to anaerobic ciliates.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] These anaerobes are useful to those with a rumen due to their ability to break down cellulose, making it bioavailable when otherwise indigestible by animals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Termites utilize anaerobic bacteria to fix and recapture nitrogen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Specifically, the termite's hindgut is full of nitrogen-fixing bacteria, whose functions depend on the nitrogen concentration of the diet.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] Acetylene reduction in termites was observed to upregulate in termites with nitrogen-poor diets, meaning that nitrogenase activity rose as the nitrogen content of the termite was reduced.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] One of the functions of termite microbiota is to recapture nitrogen from the termite's uric acid.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] This allows nitrogen conservation from a diet otherwise low in nitrogen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/anaerobe] The hindgut microbiome of different termites has been analyzed, showing 16 different anaerobic species of bacteria, including Clostridia, Enterobacteriaceae, and Gram-positive cocci.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase is a tetramer of four polypeptide chains, each over 500 amino acids long.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] It contains four iron-containing heme groups that allow the enzyme to react with hydrogen peroxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The optimum pH for human catalase is approximately 7, and has a fairly broad maximum: the rate of reaction does not change appreciably between pH 6.8 and 7.5.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The pH optimum for other catalases varies between 4 and 11 depending on the species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The optimum temperature also varies by species.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Human catalase forms a tetramer composed of four subunits, each of which can be conceptually divided into four domains.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The extensive core of each subunit is generated by an eight-stranded antiparallel β-barrel (β1-8), with nearest neighbor connectivity capped by β-barrel loops on one side and α9 loops on the other.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] A helical domain at one face of the β-barrel is composed of four C-terminal helices (α16, α17, α18, and α19) and four helices derived from residues between β4 and β5 (α4, α5, α6, and α7).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Alternative splicing may result in different protein variants.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase was first noticed in 1818 by Louis Jacques Thénard, who discovered hydrogen peroxide (H2O2).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Thénard suggested its breakdown was caused by an unknown substance.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] In 1900, Oscar Loew was the first to give it the name catalase, and found it in many plants and animals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] In 1937 catalase from beef liver was crystallized by James B.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Sumner and Alexander Dounce and the molecular weight was measured in 1938.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The amino acid sequence of bovine catalase was determined in 1969, and the three-dimensional structure in 1981.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Here Fe()-E represents the iron center of the heme group attached to the enzyme.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Fe(IV)-E(.+) is a mesomeric form of Fe(V)-E, meaning the iron is not completely oxidized to +V, but receives some stabilising electron density from the heme ligand, which is then shown as a radical cation (.+).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] As hydrogen peroxide enters the active site, it does interact with the amino acids Asn148 (asparagine at position 148) and His75, causing a proton (hydrogen ion) to transfer between the oxygen atoms.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The free oxygen atom coordinates, freeing the newly formed water molecule and Fe(IV)=O.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Fe(IV)=O reacts with a second hydrogen peroxide molecule to reform Fe(III)-E and produce water and oxygen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The reactivity of the iron center may be improved by the presence of the phenolate ligand of Tyr358 in the fifth coordination position, which can assist in the oxidation of the Fe(III) to Fe(IV).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The efficiency of the reaction may also be improved by the interactions of His75 and Asn148 with reaction intermediates.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The decomposition of hydrogen peroxide by catalase proceeds according to first-order kinetics, the rate being proportional to the hydrogen peroxide concentration.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase can also catalyze the oxidation, by hydrogen peroxide, of various metabolites and toxins, including formaldehyde, formic acid, phenols, acetaldehyde and alcohols.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The exact mechanism of this reaction is not known.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Any heavy metal ion (such as copper cations in copper(II) sulfate) can act as a noncompetitive inhibitor of catalase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] However, "Copper deficiency can lead to a reduction in catalase activity in tissues, such as heart and liver." Furthermore, the poison cyanide is a noncompetitive inhibitor of catalase at high concentrations of hydrogen peroxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Three-dimensional protein structures of the peroxidated catalase intermediates are available at the Protein Data Bank.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Hydrogen peroxide is a harmful byproduct of many normal metabolic processes; to prevent damage to cells and tissues, it must be quickly converted into other, less dangerous substances.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] To this end, catalase is frequently used by cells to rapidly catalyze the decomposition of hydrogen peroxide into less-reactive gaseous oxygen and water molecules.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Mice genetically engineered to lack catalase are initially phenotypically normal.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] However, catalase deficiency in mice may increase the likelihood of developing obesity, fatty liver, and type 2 diabetes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Some humans have very low levels of catalase (acatalasia), yet show few ill effects.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The increased oxidative stress that occurs with aging in mice is alleviated by over-expression of catalase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Over-expressing mice do not exhibit the age-associated loss of spermatozoa, testicular germ and Sertoli cells seen in wild-type mice.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Oxidative stress in wild-type mice ordinarily induces oxidative DNA damage (measured as 8-oxodG) in sperm with aging, but these damages are significantly reduced in aged catalase over-expressing mice.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Furthermore, these over-expressing mice show no decrease in age-dependent number of pups per litter.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Overexpression of catalase targeted to mitochondria extends the lifespan of mice.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] In eukaryotes, catalase is usually located in a cellular organelle called the peroxisome.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Peroxisomes in plant cells are involved in photorespiration (the use of oxygen and production of carbon dioxide) and symbiotic nitrogen fixation (the breaking apart of diatomic nitrogen (N2) to reactive nitrogen atoms).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Hydrogen peroxide is used as a potent antimicrobial agent when cells are infected with a pathogen.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase-positive pathogens, such as *Mycobacterium tuberculosis*, *Legionella pneumophila*, and *Campylobacter jejuni*, make catalase to deactivate the peroxide radicals, thus allowing them to survive unharmed within the host.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Like alcohol dehydrogenase, catalase converts ethanol to acetaldehyde, and drop-out studies in rodents suggest that it may be responsible for the majority of this reaction in the brain.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The large majority of known organisms use catalase in every organ, with particularly high concentrations occurring in the liver in mammals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Almost all aerobic microorganisms use catalase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] It is also present in some anaerobic microorganisms, such as *Methanosarcina barkeri*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase is also universal among plants and occurs in most fungi.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] One unique use of catalase occurs in the bombardier beetle.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] This beetle has two sets of liquids that are stored separately in two paired glands.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The larger of the pair, the storage chamber or reservoir, contains hydroquinones and hydrogen peroxide, while the smaller, the reaction chamber, contains catalases and peroxidases.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] To activate the noxious spray, the beetle mixes the contents of the two compartments, causing oxygen to be liberated from hydrogen peroxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The oxygen oxidizes the hydroquinones and also acts as the propellant.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The oxidation reaction is very exothermic (ΔH = −202.8 kJ/mol) and rapidly heats the mixture to the boiling point.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Long-lived queens of the termite *Reticulitermes speratus* have significantly lower oxidative damage to their DNA than non-reproductive individuals (workers and soldiers).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Queens have more than two times higher catalase activity and seven times higher expression levels of the catalase gene RsCAT1 than workers.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] It appears that the efficient antioxidant capability of termite queens can partly explain how they attain longer life.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase enzymes from various species have vastly differing optimum temperatures.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Poikilothermic animals typically have catalases with optimum temperatures in the range of 15–25 °C (59–77 °F), while mammalian or avian catalases might have optimum temperatures above 35 °C (95 °F), and catalases from plants vary depending on their growth habit.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] In contrast, catalase isolated from the hyperthermophile archaeon *Pyrobaculum calidifontis* has a temperature optimum of 90 °C (194 °F).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase is used in the food industry for removing hydrogen peroxide from milk prior to cheese production.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Another use is in food wrappers, where it prevents food from oxidizing.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase is also used in the textile industry, removing hydrogen peroxide from fabrics to make sure the material is peroxide-free.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] A minor use is in contact lens hygiene – a few lens-cleaning products disinfect the lens using a hydrogen peroxide solution; a solution containing catalase is then used to decompose the hydrogen peroxide before the lens is used again.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The catalase test is one of the three main tests used by microbiologists to identify species of bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] If the bacteria possess catalase (i.e., are catalase-positive), bubbles of oxygen are observed when a small amount of bacterial isolate is added to hydrogen peroxide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The catalase test is done by placing a drop of hydrogen peroxide on a microscope slide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] An applicator stick is touched to the colony, and the tip is then smeared onto the hydrogen peroxide drop.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] While the catalase test alone cannot identify a particular organism, it can aid identification when combined with other tests such as antibiotic resistance.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The presence of catalase in bacterial cells depends on both the growth condition and the medium used to grow the cells.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] A small sample of bacteria is collected on the end of the capillary tube, without blocking the tube, to avoid false negative results.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The opposite end is then dipped into hydrogen peroxide, which is drawn into the tube through capillary action, and turned upside down, so that the bacterial sample points downwards.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The hand holding the tube is then tapped on the bench, moving the hydrogen peroxide down until it touches the bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] If bubbles form on contact, this indicates a positive catalase result.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] This test can detect catalase-positive bacteria at concentrations above about 105 cells/mL, and is simple to use.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Neutrophils and other phagocytes use peroxide to kill bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The enzyme NADPH oxidase generates superoxide within the phagosome, which is converted via hydrogen peroxide to other oxidising substances like hypochlorous acid which kill phagocytosed pathogens.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] In individuals with chronic granulomatous disease (CGD), phagocytic peroxide production is impaired due to a defective NADPH oxidase system.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Normal cellular metabolism will still produce a small amount of peroxide and this peroxide can be used to produce hypochlorous acid to eradicate the bacterial infection.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] However, if individuals with CGD are infected with catalase-positive bacteria, the bacterial catalase can destroy the excess peroxide before it can be used to produce other oxidising substances.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] In these individuals the pathogen survives and becomes a chronic infection.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] This chronic infection is typically surrounded by macrophages in an attempt to isolate the infection.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] This wall of macrophages surrounding a pathogen is called a granuloma.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Many bacteria are catalase positive, but some are better catalase-producers than others.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Some catalase-positive bacteria and fungi include: *Nocardia, Pseudomonas, Listeria, Aspergillus, Candida, E. coli, Staphylococcus, Serratia, B. cepacia* and *H. pylori*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Acatalasia is a condition caused by homozygous mutations in CAT, resulting in a lack of catalase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Symptoms are mild and include oral ulcers.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] A heterozygous CAT mutation results in lower, but still present catalase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Low levels of catalase may play a role in the graying process of human hair.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Hydrogen peroxide is naturally produced by the body and broken down by catalase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Hydrogen peroxide can accumulate in hair follicles and if catalase levels decline, this buildup can cause oxidative stress and graying.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] These low levels of catalase are associated with old age.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Hydrogen peroxide interferes with the production of melanin, the pigment that gives hair its color.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Catalase has been shown to interact with the *ABL2* and *Abl* genes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Infection with the murine leukemia virus causes catalase activity to decline in the lungs, heart and kidneys of mice.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Conversely, dietary fish oil increased catalase activity in the heart, and kidneys of mice.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] In 1870, Schoenn discovered a formation of yellow color from the interaction of hydrogen peroxide with molybdate; then, from the middle of the 20th century, this reaction began to be used for colorimetric determination of unreacted hydrogen peroxide in the catalase activity assay.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The reaction became widely used after publications by Korolyuk et al.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] The first paper describes serum catalase assay with no buffer in the reaction medium; the latter describes the procedure based on phosphate buffer as a reaction medium.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Since phosphate ion reacts with ammonium molybdate, the use of MOPS buffer as a reaction medium is more appropriate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/catalase] Direct UV measurement of the decrease in the concentration of hydrogen peroxide is also widely used after the publications by Beers & Sizer and Aebi.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] The species is largely commensal and part of the skin flora present on most healthy adult humans' skin.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] It is usually just barely detectable on the skin of healthy preadolescents.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] It lives, among other things, primarily on fatty acids in sebum secreted by sebaceous glands in the follicles.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] It may also be found throughout the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Originally identified as *Bacillus acnes*, it was later named *Propionibacterium acnes* for its ability to generate propionic acid.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] In 2016, *P. acnes* was taxonomically reclassified as a result of biochemical and genomic studies.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] In terms of both phylogenetic tree structure and DNA G + C content, the cutaneous species was distinguishable from other species that had been previously categorized as *P. acnes*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] As part of restructuring, the novel genus *Cutibacterium* was created for the cutaneous species, including those formerly identified as *Propionibacterium acnes*, *Propionibacterium avidum*, and *Propionibacterium granulosum*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Characterization of phylotypes of *C. acnes* is an active field of research.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Acne vulgaris is a chronic inflammatory disease of the pilosebaceous unit, which includes the hair follicle, hair shaft, and sebaceous gland and about 650 million people are affected globally by this disease.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] *C. acnes* starts to colonize on the skin around 1 to 3 years prior to puberty and grows exponentially during this time.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] This is why so many teens and young adults struggle with acne.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Prescriptions to treat acne are often antibiotics.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] However, with the rise of antibiotic resistance, antibiotics are now often combined with broad-spectrum antibacterial agents such as benzoyl peroxide, and other medications like isotretinoin (commonly known by the brand name Accutane) are being used on patients with severe or resistant acne.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] The damage caused by *C. acnes* and the associated inflammation make the affected tissue more susceptible to colonization by opportunistic bacteria, such as *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Preliminary research shows healthy pores are only colonized by *C. acnes*, while unhealthy ones universally include the nonpore-resident *Staphylococcus epidermidis*, amongst other bacterial contaminants.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Whether this is a root causality, just opportunistic and a side effect, or a more complex pathological duality between *C. acnes* and this particular *Staphylococcus* species is not known.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Current research has pointed to the idea that *C. acnes* and *S. epidermidis* have a symbiotic relationship.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Both bacteria exist on the normal flora of the skin and a disrupt in balance of these bacteria on the skin can result in acne or other bacterial infection.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] In addition to contributing to skin inflammation and acne lesions, an imbalance in these bacteria may also impair the skin's ability to heal and regenerate, leading to prolonged and more severe acne outbreaks.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] This disruption can also affect the skin's overall microbiome diversity, potentially increasing susceptibility to other skin conditions such as eczema or rosacea.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Investigating the dynamics of this relationship may offer insights into novel therapeutic approaches for managing various skin disorders.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] The emergence of antibiotic-resistant *C. acnes* bacteria represents a growing problem worldwide.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] The problem is especially pronounced in North America and Europe.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] The antibiotic families that *C. acnes* are most likely to acquire resistance to are the macrolides (e.g., erythromycin and azithromycin), lincosamides (e.g., clindamycin) and tetracyclines (e.g., doxycycline and minocycline).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] However, *C. acnes* bacteria are susceptible to many types of antimicrobial chemicals found in over-the-counter antibacterial products, including benzoyl peroxide, triclosan, chloroxylenol, and chlorhexidine gluconate.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] C. acnes resistance to antibiotics has increased to 64% in 2000, up from 20% in 1979.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Treatments such as oral macrolides are often avoided because the bacteria has become resistant in most cases.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] This creates a public health issue, forcing healthcare providers to seek out other forms of treatment.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Several naturally occurring molecules and compounds are toxic to *C. acnes* bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Some essential oils such as rosemary, tea tree oil, clove oil, and citrus oils contain antibacterial chemicals.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Natural honey has also been shown to have some antibacterial properties that may be active against *C. acnes*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] The elements silver, sulfur, and copper have also been demonstrated to be toxic towards many bacteria, including *C. acnes*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Salicylic acid is a naturally occurring substance derived from plants (white willow bark and wintergreen leaves) used to promote exfoliation of the skin in order to treat acne.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] Additionally, research investigates the mechanism by which salicylic acid (SA) treats acne vulgaris.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] SA also reduces the inflammatory response of sebocytes and decreases the proliferation of *C.* *acnes*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] These results suggest that SA has a multifaceted approach in treating acne vulgaris by targeting several key factors that contribute to its development.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/cutibacterium-acnes] The minimum inhibitory concentration for SA is 4000–8000 μg/mL.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] A **facultative anaerobic organism** is an organism that makes ATP by aerobic respiration if oxygen is present, but is capable of switching to fermentation if oxygen is absent.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Some examples of facultatively anaerobic bacteria are *Staphylococcus* spp., *Escherichia coli*, *Salmonella*, *Listeria* spp., *Shewanella oneidensis* and *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Certain eukaryotes are also facultative anaerobes, including pupfish, fungi such as *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* and many aquatic invertebrates such as nereid polychaetes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] It has been observed that in mutants of *Salmonella typhimurium* that underwent mutations to be either obligate aerobes or anaerobes, there were varying levels of chromatin-remodeling proteins.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] The obligate aerobes were later found to have a defective DNA gyrase subunit A gene (*gyrA*), while obligate anaerobes were defective in topoisomerase I (*topI*).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] This indicates that topoisomerase I and its associated relaxation of chromosomal DNA is required for transcription of genes required for aerobic growth, while the opposite is true for DNA gyrase.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Additionally, in *Escherichia coli* K-12 it has been noted that phosphofructokinase (PFK) exists as a dimer under aerobic conditions and as a tetramer under anaerobic conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Given PFK's role in glycolysis, this has implications for the effect of oxygen on the glucose metabolism of *E. coli* K-12 in relation to the mechanism of the Pasteur effect.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] There may exist a core network of transcription factors (TFs) that includes the major oxygen-responsive ArcA and FNR control the adaptation of *Escherichia coli* to changes in oxygen availability.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Activities of these two regulators are indicative of spatial effects that may affect gene expression in the microaerobic range.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] It has also been observed that these oxygen-sensitive proteins are protected within the cytoplasm by oxygen consumers within the cell membrane, known as terminal oxidases.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Facultative anaerobes are able to grow in both the presence and absence of oxygen due to the expression of both aerobic and anaerobic respiratory chains using either oxygen or an alternative electron acceptor.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] For example, in the absence of oxygen, *E. coli* can use fumarate, nitrate, nitrite, dimethyl sulfoxide, or trimethylamine oxide as an electron acceptor.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] This flexibility allows facultative anaerobes to survive in a number of environments, and in environments with frequently changing conditions.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Several species of protists use a facultative anaerobic metabolism to enhance their ATP production, and some can produce dihydrogen through this process.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Since facultative anaerobes can grow in both the presence and absence of oxygen, they can survive in many different environments, adapt easily to changing conditions, and thus have a selective advantage over other bacteria.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] As a result, most life-threatening pathogens are facultative anaerobes.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] The ability of facultative anaerobic pathogens to survive without oxygen is important since their infection is shown to reduce oxygen levels in their host's gut tissue.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Moreover, the ability of facultative anaerobes to limit oxygen levels at infection sites is beneficial to them and other bacteria, as dioxygen can form reactive oxygen species (ROS).
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] These species are toxic to bacteria and can damage their DNA, among other constituents.
[src:aerotolerant-anaerobe/facultative-anaerobe] Examples of pathogenic facultative anaerobes.
